<subSubSection id="5DA66552FFCBFFC106F2F915FEFDF8A2" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="150336D9FFCBFFC106F2F915FEFDF8A2" blockId="3.[151,1437,1438,2041]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC106F2F915FED2F93F" bold="true" box="[199,322,1726,1752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D2BC4D5AFFCBFFC104ABF914FCECF93F" baseAuthorityName="Chen" baseAuthorityYear="1941" box="[670,892,1726,1753]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gonioctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanfani">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC104ABF914FCECF93F" box="[670,892,1726,1753]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">Gonioctena kanfani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in that the pronotum lacks spots and the elytral punctures are arranged in almost regular single rows. However, 
<taxonomicName id="D2BC4D5AFFCBFFC1055CF948FC5FF91B" authority="Cho, 2022" authorityName="Cho" authorityYear="2022" box="[873,975,1762,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gonioctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lukasi" status="new species">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC1055CF948FCEDF91A" box="[873,893,1763,1789]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC105B9F949FC5FF91B" box="[908,975,1762,1788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">lukasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC105E2F949FBF1F91B" bold="true" box="[983,1121,1762,1788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3CFB57B0FFCBFFC105E2F949FBF1F91B" box="[983,1121,1762,1788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished by the median lobe which is strongly medially constricted in dorsal view and greatly expanded in lateral view (long and thin in 
<taxonomicName id="D2BC4D5AFFCBFFC106D2F880FECDF8A3" baseAuthorityName="Chen" baseAuthorityYear="1941" box="[231,349,1834,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gonioctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanfani">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC106D2F880FF6BF8A2" box="[231,251,1835,1861]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">G</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC1073CF881FECDF8A3" box="[265,349,1834,1860]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">kanfani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5DA66552FFCBFFC706F2F8E5FD6AFEA6" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="116" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" type="description">
<paragraph id="150336D9FFCBFFC106F2F8E5FCEEF81E" blockId="3.[151,1437,1438,2041]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCBFFC106F2F8E5FEC9F88F" bold="true" box="[199,345,1870,1896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">Description.</emphasis>
Measurements in mm (n = 5): Length of body: 6.40–8.30 (mean 7.46); width of body: 3.65–4.77 (mean 4.26); height of body: 2.30–3.07 (mean 2.73); width of head: 1.86–2.16 (mean 2.01); interocular distance: 1.26–1.47 (mean 1.36); width of apex of pronotum: 2.12–2.57 (mean 2.35); width of base of pronotum: 3.12–3.83 (mean 3.53); maximum width of pronotum: 3.20–3.92 (mean 3.58); length of pronotum along midline: 1.54–1.83 (mean 1.71); length of elytra along suture: 4.68–6.10 (mean 5.44).
</paragraph>
<caption id="41C36651FFCCFFC606A2FB63FAC0FB38" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6610115" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6610115" box="[151,1360,1224,1248]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6610115/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="115" startId="4.[151,264,1224,1248]" targetBox="[218,1347,196,1185]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="150336D9FFCCFFC606A2FB63FAC0FB38" blockId="4.[151,1360,1224,1248]" box="[151,1360,1224,1248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC606A2FB63FEABFB07" bold="true" box="[151,315,1224,1248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">FIGURES 3–4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D2BC4D5AFFCCFFC60774FB63FE6AFB07" authority="Cho, 2022" authorityName="Cho" authorityYear="2022" box="[321,506,1224,1248]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Gonioctena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lukasi" status="new species">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC60774FB63FE6AFB07" box="[321,506,1224,1248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Gonioctena lukasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC60435FB63FDEDFB07" bold="true" box="[512,637,1224,1248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="3CFB57B0FFCCFFC60435FB63FDEDFB07" box="[512,637,1224,1248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, male holotype. 3: dorsal habitus, 4: lateral habitus. Scale bar: 1.0 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="150336D9FFCCFFC706F2FAA5FD6AFEA6" blockId="4.[151,1437,1294,2041]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,429]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="116" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
Body oblong-ovate and moderately convex (
<figureCitation id="8D872A5CFFCCFFC604F6FAA5FCBDFACF" box="[707,813,1294,1320]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1224,1248]" captionTargetBox="[218,1347,196,1185]" captionTargetId="figure-20@4.[151,1435,181,1200]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3–4. Gonioctena lukasi new species, male holotype. 3: dorsal habitus, 4: lateral habitus. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6610115" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6610115/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Figs 3, 4</figureCitation>
). Head and pronotum dark reddish-brown to greenishblack with dull metallic lustre. Mouthparts dark reddish-brown with apices of mandibles black. Antennomeres I–V reddish-brown; VI–VII darkened; VIII–XI black. Elytra greenish-black with bright metallic lustre; humeri each with black spot surrounded by yellowish-brown circle. Venter and legs dark reddish-brown, partially darkened. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC60362FAD1FA0CFA73" bold="true" box="[1367,1436,1402,1429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC60362FAD1FA05FA72" bold="true" box="[1367,1429,1402,1429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Vertex weakly convex, with moderately dense punctures, becoming denser toward sides. Frontal suture V-shaped, coronal suture weak. Frons flat, strongly depressed at anterior margin, covered with dense punctures. Clypeus rather narrow and trapezoidal.Anterior margin of labrum weakly concave. Mandibles with two sharp apical teeth and deep lateral excavations for maxillary palpomeres. Maxillary palpi four-segmented with apical palpomeres moderately widened, truncate apically. Antennae almost reaching pronotal base; antennomere I robust and longest; II longer than III; III longer than IV; VI–X widened; XI about 1.33 times as long as wide. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC60212F9F9FB33F98B" bold="true" box="[1063,1187,1618,1644]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC60212F9F9FB0CF98B" bold="true" box="[1063,1180,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Pronotum</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
In dorsal view widest near base, moderately convexly narrowed anteriorly, anterior angles strongly produced. Anterior and lateral margins bordered; lateral margins usually distinct in dorsal view. Trichobothria absent from anterior angles, present on posterior angles. Disc with sparse to dense punctures; lateral sides with much larger and denser punctures, partially confluent; interspaces with fine and moderately dense punctures. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC605B2F949FB93F91B" bold="true" box="[903,1027,1762,1789]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<taxonomicName id="D2BC4D5AFFCCFFC605B2F949FC6CF91A" box="[903,1020,1762,1789]" class="Trilobita" family="Styginidae" genus="Scutellum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Corynexochida" pageId="4" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC605B2F949FC6CF91A" bold="true" box="[903,1020,1762,1789]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Scutellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Slightly wider than long, narrowed posteriorly. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC6072BF8ADFEFCF8C7" bold="true" box="[286,364,1798,1825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC6072BF8ADFEF6F8C6" bold="true" box="[286,358,1798,1825]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Elytra</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
In dorsal view moderately widened posteriorly, widest beyond middle, roundly narrowed posteriorly. Humeral calli well developed. Disc with 11 almost regular rows of large punctures, including short scutellar row, with few strial punctures out of alignment; interspaces with fine and sparse punctures. Epipleura mostly visible (except apical 2/5) in lateral view. Hind wings well developed. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC6058BF8D9FB80F86B" bold="true" box="[958,1040,1906,1932]" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCCFFC6058BF8D9FB99F86B" bold="true" box="[958,1033,1906,1932]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="115">Venter</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Pronotal hypomera weakly rugose with coarse punctures on anterior 1/5. Prosternum with coarse and dense punctures bearing long setae; prosternal process enlarged apically, bordered laterally, with sparse punctures. Metaventrite with minute and sparse punctures medially, large and dense punctures laterally. Abdominal ventrites with sparse to dense punctures bearing short setae; apex of last visible abdominal ventrite distinctly depressed in male. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCDFFC705E7FF3CFB9FFF56" bold="true" box="[978,1039,151,177]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCDFFC705E7FF3CFB98FF56" bold="true" box="[978,1032,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Legs</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Moderately robust. Tibiae widened apically with tooth-like projections. Forelegs with tarsomere I slightly narrower than III in male; distinctly narrower than III in female. Tarsal claws appendiculate. 
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCDFFC70496FF75FC85FF1E" bold="true" box="[675,789,222,249]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCDFFC70496FF75FC9EFF1E" bold="true" box="[675,782,222,249]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Median lobe in dorsal view strongly medially constricted and with thin apical lobe (
<figureCitation id="8D872A5CFFCDFFC7078DFEA8FE6BFEFA" box="[440,507,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–11" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1744,1768]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,465,1709]" captionTargetId="figure-114@7.[151,1436,453,1721]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 7–11. Gonioctena species, male genitalia. 7: G. jolantae new species (dorsal, apico-dorsal &amp; lateral), 8: G. lukasi new species (dorsal &amp; lateral), 9: G. kanfani (Chen, 1941) (apico-dorsal &amp; lateral, redrawn from Yang et al. 2014), 10: G. kamikawai (Chûjô, 1958) (dorsal, apico-dorsal &amp; lateral), 11: G. fujiana Cho &amp; Borowiec, 2016 (dorsal, apico-dorsal &amp; lateral). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6610119" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6610119/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); in lateral view apical 1/2 greatly enlarged with apical process curved and tapered; distal tip of flagellum trifurcated. Spermatheca absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5DA66552FFCDFFC706F2FEE0FD56FE6E" pageId="5" pageNumber="116" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="150336D9FFCDFFC706F2FEE0FD56FE6E" blockId="5.[151,1436,151,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis id="27C8EACBFFCDFFC706F2FEE0FEDEFE82" bold="true" box="[199,334,331,357]" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is dedicated to my colleague Dr. Lukáš Sekerka (National Museum, 
<collectingCountry id="6DAB7649FFCDFFC702EFFEE0FA01FE81" box="[1242,1425,331,358]" name="Czech Republic" pageId="5" pageNumber="116">Czech Republic</collectingCountry>
), who kindly sent me the material for investigation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
